variations$en: Cyber harassment can be in the form of derogatory or insulting comments made in chat rooms, e-mail, block postings, or comments on social networking sites. Those responsible for harassment are often difficult to track as the perpetrator is often anonymous.

formData.text$en: There have always been people who choose to  behave like a bully and those who are unfortunate targets. One theory is that cyberbullies have difficulty feeling empathy for others. Low empathy has certainly been attributed to increased use of technology and less real-world social interaction.
variations$en: This is because cyberbullying also allows a bully to feel more powerful. Through the use of technology, a cyberbully can easily and effortlessly unleash a torrent of torment at any time, all from the safe harbor of their own home, with little concern or repercussions.
A lack of parental monitoring is another contributing factor, as is the desire to achieve popularity through acts they feel resonate well with their peers and associates.
Cyberbullies generally have the intention of creating harm when they engage in online bullying.

formData.text$en: However, bullying can still take place without intention if a victim perceives actions to be harmful.
variations$en: Regardless of the reasons, cyberbullies sometimes face their own dark futures. Studies show that kids who bully others are more likely to abuse drugs and alcohol, engage in fights and criminal behavior, drop out of school, or be abusive toward their partners or their children.

Even the bystanders and witnesses are not immune to the effects of cyberbullying. They may also have an increased likelihood of experimenting with drugs and alcohol at an early age or suffering emotional distress and mental health problems.

As an interesting side note, one study states that cyberbullying is more likely to occur between current or former friends. The report further states that cyberbullying occurs seven times more frequently among teens who know each other than among people who had never been friends or dated

formData.text$en: 2 kinds of Psychotherapies are particularly effective in helping a victim of cyberbullying recover from its effects:
Assertiveness training:   Victims of cyberbullying often need help in building their confidence to stand up to their bullies.
Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT):  Many victims of cyberbullying tend to develop certain safety behaviors in order to deal with resulting depression or anxiety.
variations$en: CBT helps victims overcome these as it is effective in retraining the victim so that they may be able to change their behaviors or thoughts for a positive change in their daily life
